WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Welcome back to the Data Science Lab. I'm Libby. I run community here at Posit, and I'm joined by Isabella Velazquez. Isabella, would you like to say hello?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Hi, everyone. Thanks for joining.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I am so excited to be joined today by our lab manager, our guest lab manager, Davis Vaughan. Davis, would you like to say a quick hello and tell us who you are and what you do?

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Sure. Hi, everyone. It's nice to be here. I'm a software engineer at Posit. I work on the Positron teams and the tidyverse teams. I work on dplyr, tidyr. I also am the co-creator of air, the R formatter.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Nice. All right, Davis, what are you going to be showing us today on the lab?

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:11.000
So, yeah, I figured today we could talk about dplyr 1.2 a little bit. It'd be kind of fun to just kind of go over some of the new functions, like filter out and recode values and replace values, and then maybe also a little bit about like how functions in the tidyverse are lifecycled.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Like, what does it mean to be superseded? What does it mean to be deprecated? And what is the difference?

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:24.000
How do decisions get made? What kind of conversations are had behind the scenes? That's what I really want to know. I'm going to ask some nosy questions about that.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Another thing that we will briefly touch on is also like how – well, not briefly touch on. This is going to be the theme.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:40.000
How community-driven development happens and why community is such a huge part of the development of open source packages.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And also, Davis will talk a little bit about wife-driven development.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:02:01.000
All right, everybody, let's get ready to watch Davis share his screen and walk through a couple of things for us, the first one being we have a new function called recode values.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:11.000
This one's really exciting for me because I have had a janky workaround to recode values for a long time, and I'm not the only one who had that janky workaround.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Crystal Lewis also had that janky workaround, and we've all been sort of circumnavigating a slight hole that was in the dplyr suite of functions.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So, Davis, would you be willing to walk us through a demo of why we needed this new function and what it does?

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Do you happen to have the BlueSky post from either you or Crystal just about the issue?

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
You know what?

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.000
I can go ahead and find it, yeah.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Yeah, well, we'll find it. There's a BlueSky post where somebody had posted – if you're not on BlueSky, get there. The RStats data BlueSky scene is really, really great.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Somebody posted a question like, hey, how can I recode these values based on a named list, I think is what it was, right?

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And everybody was chiming in and being like, oh, we can do different things.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
I'm like, oh, here's my workaround, and Crystal Lewis was like, me too, I have the same workaround.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Yeah, so I'll just show you.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Yep, that's it. There's my screen chat.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Yeah, so we were all, like, super confused about this whole idea. It's not going to look very pretty for a second.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.000
That's okay.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So, like, I have a named list here, right? This is like a Likert encoding, where, like, one means strongly disagree, five means strongly agree, and then there's everything in between.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And you might have the data in the form of just the numbers, and you want to recode that using this mapping into the actual, like, word descriptions.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And there was this whole discussion that went on of, like, what's the best way to do that?

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And the kind of hacky solution was using a superseded dplyr function called recode, plus this, like, triple bang type thing to get that to work.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
From Arlang. It's an Arlang operator.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Yeah.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
But it's a very cool Arlang operator, okay? Like, it's still so valid. It's really, really cool.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
It is cool. It is valid.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Wouldn't it be great to, like, have a way to just do this without that?

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So, it got a lot of traction, and, like, it got us thinking of, like, why is this so stupidly difficult?

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
So, we clearly figured out there was some kind of, like, hole here.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So, the hole was filled by recode values.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So, just, like, a little bit of how this works, right?

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
So, you've got your Likert scores here.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
It's just a column in your Tybl.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And, like, there's some typical other way you might do this if you didn't have, like, a lookup table on the side,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
where you might go through case win, and you might say, you know, if score is one, strongly disagree.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
If score is two, disagree, and so on.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And that works. I mean, it's wordy, but it works.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And, like, one of the nice things about this new function called recode values is that it takes this, like, common bit of score

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
and says, hey, you can actually, like, pipe that thing in.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
We recognize that all of the individual cases are going to be comparing to score.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
So, you can pull that to the front.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So, now it's score, and I want to recode all of the individual values from score,

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.000
where one becomes disagree, two becomes strongly disagree, two becomes disagree, and so on.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
So, you can kind of get rid of this score equal, equal bit.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
So, that's nice as, like, one step in the right direction.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
But remember, we had that, like, lookup table thing that we cared about.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So, what we can do is actually, like, if you squint at recode values here, it kind of looks like a lookup table.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Like, it's on the left-hand side, it's mapping to the right-hand side, and that looks pretty nice.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So, what we can do is make that more explicit.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Like, we can pull that out into a table called lookup.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And instead of this, like, very familiar case-winning interface,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:17.000
we can use an alternate interface where you supply from and to columns directly,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:22.000
where I can say, from this lookup table, like, where it's one through five,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
map that to these words, strongly disagree, disagree, and so on.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So, recode score from that to that.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And that works great.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:38.000
And that is kind of the answer to that, like, how do we do this recode bang, bang, bang thing?

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Like, why is this so hard?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Like, we can now pull this really nice lookup table out separately and supply it in our pipeline,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
which is especially really nice if you have a really long pipeline,

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
and things get, like, it just lets you focus on actually what you're doing rather than the mapping itself.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And the last thing I'll say about it before we stop is this little bit here.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Like, it's very common, in my experience, for this lookup table to not be inline.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
It's actually from CSV file somewhere else.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So, that makes, like, the recode bang, bang, bang even, like, it's, like, your only option

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
because you couldn't actually inline it with the case win before.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So, now, if you did have it in a CSV, it's just as easy as reading it in, supplying it here.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Yes, and I want to reemphasize for everybody that everybody has a different type of need, right?

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Like, whatever your experience is of needing a function, most people need it in a different way.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Everything is so, so unique, right?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
So, there are a lot of responses that are, like, why would I ever need this?

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
I've never needed it before.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:44.000
You just specifically have not happened to need it, but then other people have really, really needed it, right?

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So, if you've ever only written pretty short case win statements and you've only ever needed maybe three or four things in your case win,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:58.000
maybe up to, like, 10, 11, then it's possible you haven't experienced needing 800 levels of case win, right?

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Like, it's possible that you haven't worked with really wild survey data or really, really wild, you know,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.000
longitudinal data that has needed tons and tons of recoding.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:18.000
And in those instances, a thing like this that abstracts away all of the complications can be really magical because Davis is right.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Those lookup tables exist on their own.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:30.000
In fact, I just sent Isabella some survey data yesterday that had a CSV lookup table all on its own that I created that had, you know, 40 or something entries in it.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
That's usually just the way that it goes.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:44.000
So, the real thing that I want to talk about behind this with Davis is actually the different little bits and pieces that came together to tell him it was time to add a function to dPlayer

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:52.000
because it wasn't just that blue sky post and it wasn't just me talking about it, Crystal Lewis, making a blog post about it.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Davis, what all was going on behind the scenes that came together for you to say, like, well, it's definitely time to take action?

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
Because you'd already been thinking about it when I messaged you about it, right?

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Yeah, we've had, like, we've had issues on the dPlayer tracker for years of, like, you know, you superseded recode, but, like, you didn't give us anything better.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Like, it just feels like there's some missing holes where, like, you superseded this function, but there wasn't a complete replacement.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And, like, at the time, we just kind of, like, looked at that and we were like, did we? I don't really know.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.000
But, like, you know, then you see all this community impact of, like, yeah, you really did.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
Like, here's the exact example of, like, the hole that you're missing some kind of answer for.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And that really, like, nails down the point of, like, yeah, we think that there really is a gap here.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:39.000
We think we could do something better.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
Like, we agree that recode probably wasn't the best API to begin with.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
We don't feel bad about that decision.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
But, like, we didn't fill the hole with something better.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Right.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
So there was already stuff going on behind the scenes.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
And this brings me to GitHub repos.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Often when there's a feature that you want added to something, you will hear us in the sort of general open source community say go thumbs up that issue.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
It's the best way for us to know that you care about it.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
It's even more important than adding a comment.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Right.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:16.000
If you add a comment on an issue that says this is really important to me, it's actually less impactful than putting a thumbs up.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
So, Davis, can you walk through what that looks like?

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
Like, how does someone go thumbs up an issue?

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And then how do you use that to filter and find things that are valuable to the community?

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
Sure.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
I have a good example, actually.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
So I work on Positron.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Positron is the new data science IDE from Posit.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:45.000
And, like, we will go over in the issues list over here in Positron.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And, like, something that we do, like, fairly often is go over here and sort by the number of thumbs up.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And you probably won't be surprised if you're using Positron often that Cordo inline output is the number one thumbs up issue with over 106 thumbs up.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:15.000
So if you wanted to add your support to request this feature, you could hit the little smiley face here and thumbs up.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And then it would bump to 107.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So, you know, I really want Cordo inline output.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So let's just do that.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.000
And we use this a lot.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Like, we go in here and we sort by, like, you know, how many thumbs up.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:33.000
And this is kind of some kind of impact or some kind of guide of, like, what does the community care about.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Perfect.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
All right.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
So, everybody, the main issue, post, reaction, add a thumbs up.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
That lets people know that you're really excited about it.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And I really encourage you to go check out Positron's GitHub.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Go look at all the open issues.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
But also go check out Cordo.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
Go check out all kinds of things.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
I want to hop over to a couple of questions.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Mike had asked if you could show us how packages like dplyr are created along with functions, it would be helpful.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Because there are a number of moving parts to the package.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
We're not going to go that deep today, Mike.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:14.000
We're going to talk about more surface level stuff, like adding new functions to an established package and deprecating functions.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
But that's a fantastic idea.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:24.000
We did have Kylie Ainsley on a few weeks ago who talked about a little bit about our package.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
Not package development, but the package structure, at least.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
I think it would be a great idea to talk more about packages in a future episode.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:41.000
We also had a question from Nathan that was, so, if we have a data dictionary, we could use recode with across to apply the right values to the right question?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:49.000
You can put, you can use almost all of these with across to go across all of your questions.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:55.000
So, you could do across all or you could do something like starts with, right?

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
Like to grab all of your columns that start with something.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Let's say all of your questions in your survey start with like a question underscore or Q underscore.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.000
Then you can, yeah, grab all of those and apply it all across those and mutate.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
And we might be able to show that with Davis as well.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I was trying to find that example that you asked me to add.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:28.000
Yeah, I pushed Davis to add this because often when there's not something in a vignette that extends the function into using across or into using starts with or something like that,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
I find that learners, when I'm teaching, get really stuck.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
They're like, okay, I know that this function does this.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:38.000
I know that there's the ability to apply it across other columns, but I don't know how to put those pieces together.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So, I think this is kind of what they're asking for, right?

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
You have multiple columns where they're all Likert codes and they're all grouped by this common name of score.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:56.000
So, you could say if it starts with score, I want to recode those values using that table that we had before from two.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And then it goes ahead and recodes all of those columns that match score.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Yes, perfect.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
And then Noor had asked, why dplyr 1.2 as opposed to 2.0?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Is there a limit, a threshold where you're like, aha, we've reached 2.0?

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Yeah, the 1.0 release of dplyr was a chance for us to...

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Typically, these major releases like 1.0 and 2.0 are reserved for I really, really want to break something that really might affect a lot of people's code.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:37.000
We have made some seriously bad decision and we think that there's something much better now.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:44.000
And we regret something deeply and we'd like to break it, but we'd like to let people know that there's some big reason we're going to break it.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:49.000
So, it seems unlikely that we will ever have a dplyr 2.0 at this point.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.000
We feel mostly pretty good about all the decisions that we've made.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.000
I could regret those words so fast. It might happen.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.000
But most of the dplyr releases will be like 1.2, 1.3.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:07.000
And anything that are really small, just bug fixes, will be like 1.2.1.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.000
It's not too much to worry about in a very small patch release.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:16.000
All right, perfect. And did we touch on what a tidy up is?

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Not yet.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:24.000
You might have heard us, if we were talking on Blue Sky or we're posting on LinkedIn, you might have seen the phrase tidy up.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Can you talk a little bit about what that means?

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:36.000
Sure. So, one of the big ways that we get feedback from the community, in addition to Blue Sky and LinkedIn and kind of talking with you all there,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:41.000
is the somewhat new-ish process that we use called tidy ups.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:48.000
If you're familiar with PEPs from the Python ecosystem, which is like a Python enhancement proposal,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:54.000
tidy ups are kind of our community-facing similar-ish idea.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:00.000
So, they live here under Tidyverse, Tidy Ups on GitHub. We have eight of them.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:06.000
And each of these is some kind of proposed large change to the Tidyverse.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:14.000
Either it's some kind of breaking change or some kind of totally new feature that's pretty big and we'd like to get it right the first time around.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:19.000
So, for like recoding and replacing, for example, since we've gotten this wrong...

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
Can you zoom in just a little bit, David?

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.000
Oh, yes. Yes, of course.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
Just a little click, click. Yeah, awesome.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:29.000
Since we got this wrong so many times before, we decided to do a tidy up to get a lot of community feedback

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
to make sure that we got it right this time around.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So, you can go through and read this. It's just like a markdown document.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:44.000
I'll show you the outline. Oh, actually, it's in here now.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
The outline is kind of just the most interesting thing to look at real quick.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:51.000
You can get a general vibe of our motivation for this function.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.000
All these examples of what you might have done instead.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Here's how it's better than X, Y, and Z.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And how are we going to preserve backwards compatibility?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
How do you teach this if you're a teacher?

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:08.000
We try to think of as many things as possible in this tidy up of what could be interesting for people.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.000
And then we release it for the community to kind of give feedback on this markdown document.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
And a lot of people did, which is great.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:22.000
We had a lot of people come through and say all kinds of things they do or don't like about it.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
And people also gave a lot of feedback for this one on Blue Sky and LinkedIn, which we used as well.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
We kind of incorporated everything in here. So, it was great.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:37.000
If you ever see tidy ups out in the wild, this is your chance to weigh in on this package that we all use

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
and that many, many people contribute to and maintain.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:47.000
I really want to encourage everybody, if you've never, ever participated in open source development before,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
to go through and read things. Read the comments of others.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
If you are ever nervous about commenting, hop on the Discord and let us know.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
Like, hey, I really want to add this comment, but I don't know if this is the right thing to do.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Ask somebody, and they can help you. I'll chime in and help as well.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
Or Isabella will, or Daniel. Somebody will hold your hand a little bit.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
