And if they're dead, when did they die, I think, or the date of this kind of information here.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:50.000
So like we might have some question where you want to know, you want to drop the rows where two things are happening at once.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
The patient is deceased.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And the year of that kind of information was before 2012.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So like two things.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
Patient is deceased.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:01.000
That's the deceased column.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
And the year was before 2012.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
That goes with the date column.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:12.000
So you could like directly translate this into a filter statement where it's like they're deceased.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
The date is before 2012.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.000
And rather than keeping those rows, I'm looking to drop those rows.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:23.000
So you could like wrap this whole thing in parentheses and just put a not in front of it.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
That's kind of your most direct translation.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
And that kind of works, except it's not exactly what you want.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And it's a little bit subtle to understand why this isn't exactly what you want.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:44.000
But if you think about the question, like I want to drop like only when I know that that patient is deceased.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:49.000
And I want to drop rows only when I know that the year was before 2012.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:57.000
So if you look at the results here, what you'll notice is that my wife, Sarah, has been dropped out of this kind of data set here.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Because we don't actually know that she's deceased or what the date was.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.000
But it has dropped her out of this data set kind of by accident.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
We dropped too many rows.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:17.000
And the reason for that is kind of complicated, but it has to do with how filter works with missing values.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And what you end up having to do instead, you just kind of start adding in these like really, really ugly like deceased and it's not in A.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:32.000
It's before 2012 and it's not in A.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.000
And like you end up kind of squinting at this for a while and maybe you end up with the right answer.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.000
You're like, okay, now I finally got like what I was looking for.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:45.000
Like if I don't know the answer, I still want to keep that row.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And typically like that's what you're actually after when your question, your kind of problem statement up top says like I want to filter out specific rows.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
Like you typically don't want to drop the missing values.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:06.000
So what we've ended up with with filter out is a way for you to kind of directly translate your question right into code as it was before.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:12.000
And keep that intent of I don't want to drop the missing values either.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:21.000
Like if it's this lets you say I only want to drop the deceased and I only want to drop where I know date is before 2012.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:26.000
Since you don't know that about say max here, that row sticks around.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
Hopefully that makes a little bit of sense.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:36.000
But the general guideline at the bottom here is if you decide you only want to keep rows, like if that's how you're framing the problem in your head, you want to filter.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:42.000
If you're kind of thinking about it as I want to get rid of some stuff, I want to drop rows, you probably want filter out.

